Drill: Formulating good research questions

What is the 1994 rate of juvenile delinquency in the U.S.?

Good

What can we do to reduce juvenile delinquency in the U.S.?

Bad - What statistical characteristics of juvenile deliquents can be altered to reduce juvenile delinquency in the U.S. by >%5?

Does education play a role in reducing juvenile delinquents' return to crime?

Bad - After a juvenile delinquent has been convicted, do educational programs significantly reduce the rate of return to crime?  

How many customers does AT&T currently serve in Washington, DC?

Bad - Do the customers that AT&T serves in Washington, D.C., have significant differences in age, race and earnings?

What factors lead consumers to choose AT&T over other service providers?

Good

How can AT&T attract more customers?

Bad - With the known factors that cause consumers to choose AT&T, what A/B tests can be run to attract more customers?

Why did the Challenger Shuttle explode?

Bad - What mechanical factors and human errors lead ot the explosion of the Challenger Shuttle?

Which genes are associated with increased risk of breast cancer?

Bad - Are there specific genes associated with increased risks of breast cancer?

Is it better to read to children at night or in the morning?

Good

How does Googleâ€™s search algorithm work?

Bad - What key inputs does Google use in it's algorithm to return results to the user?